english:
  title: Memorial in Response to the Royal Edict Summoning Aid Against the Jurchen
  author: Park Seung-jung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the fifth of this month, Observer-in-Chief Yelü Tzu-ch'un and others from Yongzhou arrived bearing an imperial edict. The sovereign's command to me read as follows:

    "Of late, the wild Jurchen tribes have raided our borders. Though we have dispatched troops to sweep them away along multiple routes, I fear that pressed by adversity, they may flee into their own territories and fortify themselves in remote strongholds, where they hide to escape justice while bringing terror and chaos to your people. As you yourself have previously reported, these Jurchen constantly harass your lands. Now that we raise our armies for their chastisement, seize this moment of our might. You too must swiftly marshal your forces, secure the vital passes by the best routes, and meet our army to combine our strength and eliminate this pestilence. Trapped between us, they cannot escape. This serves both our interests. Follow my command without delay. When my emissary returns, submit a full accounting of all measures taken."

    The royal messenger arrived with urgency; the imperial words were grave beyond measure. How could my heart not tremble with reverence and uncertainty?

    ---

    I humbly reflect that Your Majesty possesses the valor Heaven bestows and virtue that rises daily. Your sacred merit and lofty deeds shine above all hundred rulers of old; your deep benevolence and abundant grace suffuse all the ten thousand lands. Thus all who possess wisdom sing your praises and bow before you, and all living things are stirred to motion—none dare resist, betray righteousness, or disorder the realm.

    Yet these Jurchen alone are brutish by nature and arrogant in repute. In ages past they required the rod of force; now they cannot be won by wisdom. They indulge their base instincts and inflict their poison at will—hardly worthy of troubling Heaven's wrath. We need only drive them out.

    Still, when the Miao people showed disrespect, even sage Shun feared unrest in the Middle Kingdom; when the demon Chiyou wreaked havoc, even the Yellow Emperor could not abandon the sword. Thus you have gathered your forces and commenced the campaign. It is as when a great mountain crushes an egg, when a blazing fire consumes dry brush—one wave of the sacred banner, and the cunning nest shall crumble to dust.

    Yet you wisely feared they might flee into our realm and bring ruin to our people. Therefore you sent this envoy first, kindling our resolve through your grace. Reading your edicts, I recognize the depth of your protection; my heart is moved beyond measure, yet I know not how to repay such kindness.

    Our small realm borders their savage lands and suffers their constant raids. Our soldiers grow weary, our granaries empty. These vile brigands dwell in deep and treacherous fastnesses, living by water and grass, moving swift as wind and lightning. Without Heaven's soldiers to punish them, how could we ever avenge our nation's wrongs? We await your tigers and bears to break their sheep and dogs, so that joining our strength to your mighty sweep, we may fulfill the loyalty of Chong-erh serving his king and never abandon the mandate to chastise the barbarians.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yelü Tzu-ch''un (耶律資春): A Khitan official sent as an imperial envoy.'
    - The historical references to Sage Shun, the demon Chiyou, and the Yellow Emperor invoke classical precedents for military campaigns against uncivilized peoples.
    - Chong-erh (重耳) refers to Duke Wen of Jin (晉文公), a model of virtuous loyalty to the Zhou king.
    - The poem employs the classical memorial form (표) to blend gratitude for imperial support with a detailed account of the realm's military circumstances.
